      "label": "Transcript",
      "value": "State of South Carolina Charleston District Memorandum of Agreement made this Day of AD 1865 between of Plantation Parish of St Johns Berkley State and District aforesaid Planter and the undersigned freed-men and freed-women- to be in force until the Day of AD 186 . 1. The said: agrees to permit the said freedmen and freedwomen to cultivate the crops already planted by them on his land, and to continue to occupy their present dwelling houses until the Day of AD 186 unless their conduct in the mean time shall be such as to require their removal by or with the consent of 2. The said freedmen and freedwomen agree to work faithfully under the direction of a foreman to be chosen by the said planter or his agent and to submit at all times and in all places to his direction and control and to behave in a respectful and orderly manner. 3 The said freedmen and freedwomen agree to labour ten hours every day if required Sundays only excepted, and if not employed in the cultivation of the crops to labour on such other work as may be necessary to the profitable working of the plantation and to keeping the same in good order. It shall be the duty of the foreman to report to the owner of the plantation or to his Agent all cases of idleness imperfect work or absenteeism all thefts unauthorized use or abuse of any property whatsoever committed to their charge; which cases whether reported by the foreman or otherwise ascertained shall be submitted to [End Page 1] to be visited with such punishment or penalties as he may deem fit. 4. The crops shall be harvested prepared for market and put in barns by the said freedmen and freedwomen under the direction of the said or his agent after which the said crops shall be divided into two equal parts; one part to be reserved by the said for his individual use and the other part to be turned over to the said freedmen and freedwomen to be divided among themselves The said freedmen and freedwomen hereby acknowledge to have already received at the hands of the said provisions for themselves and families sufficient for their support and maintenance until the Day of AD 186 . 5 The foreman shall detail each night from the said freedmen two watchmen or guards, who shall be responsible for the general good order and welfare of the plantation. 6. Should any of the said freedmen or freedwomen absent themselves from the plantation without the permission of the said he or she shall forfeit all share or interest in the crops. [End Page 2] * \"the nearest military commander or office commanding nearest military [illegible] or Captain [Monlith?] little should be here invited as he may direct [End Page 3]"
